{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15a5c81d-6a34-4726-a1a4-6085eb5aac26","content":"The template has a solid start but has a few issues before it's NuGet-ready:\n\n**Critical:**\n- **No template source files** — the directory only contains `.template.config/`. You need actual project files (`.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) for the template to produce anything.\n- **`Framework` symbol missing `replaces`** — the parameter is defined but never substituted. Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or a placeholder token) so the chosen framework actually gets written into your `.csproj`'s `<TargetFramework>`.\n\n**Recommended:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation.\n- **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — set to `true` so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n- **Missing `defaultName`** — e.g. `\"defaultName\": \"MyWebApi1\"` gives a fallback when no `-n` is provided.\n- **No NuGet packaging project** — you'll need a `.csproj` (with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>`) or a `.nuspec` to actually `dotnet pack` this into a `.nupkg`.\n\n**Verdict:** Not ready to publish yet. Add the template source files and fix the `Framework` symbol first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28e7bd5b-abf5-4924-b207-8fb7d9faf88a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. Let me check what's required for a .NET template package.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** – Best practice to include `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** – Recommended for template packs with multiple related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** – Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** – Common to set this to `true` for project templates.\n\n\n5. **The `sourceName` replacement** – This looks fine; it will replace \"MyWebApi\" with the user-provided name.\n6. **Missing `replaces` property for the `Framework` symbol** – The symbol is defined but won't actually substitute into project files, which is a functional problem.\n7. **No `defaultName`** – Not critical but recommended.\n8. **The directory only contains `.template.config`** – There are no actual template source files visible, which is critical for publishing.\n\nThe most pressing issues are the missing template source files and the `Framework` symbol not being wired up to replace values in the actual project files.","outputTokens":805},"id":"f0679c82-4307-4df5-8ea5-6eb70ba3c351","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:41:55.916Z","parentId":"4f06ecff-b107-483d-a619-4d3a0bc071bc"}
